# LC 217 — Contains Duplicate

## Problem

Given an integer array `nums`, return `true` if any value appears **at least twice**, and `false` if every element is distinct.

---

## Approach 1: Brute Force (Nested Loop)

### Intuition

Compare every pair of elements. If any two are equal, return `true`. If the entire loop finishes without finding a match, return `false`.

```python
def containsDuplicate_bruteforce(nums):
    for i in range(len(nums)):
        for j in range(i + 1, len(nums)):
            if nums[i] == nums[j]:
                return True
    return False
```

### Complexity

| | |
|---|---|
| **Time** | O(n²) — every pair is compared |
| **Space** | O(1) — no extra data structures |

---

## Approach 2: Optimal (Hash Set)

### Intuition

Walk through the array once. For each number, check if it already exists in a hash set — if yes, we found a duplicate. If no, add it to the set and move on.

```python
def containsDuplicate(nums):
    seen = set()

    for num in nums:
        if num in seen:       # O(1) lookup
            return True
        seen.add(num)         # O(1) insert

    return False
```

### Complexity

| | |
|---|---|
| **Time** | O(n) — single pass, O(1) lookup and insert at each step |
| **Space** | O(n) — hash set stores up to n elements |

---

## Comparison

| | BF: Nested Loop | Optimal: Hash Set |
|---|---|---|
| **Time** | O(n²) | O(n) ✅ |
| **Space** | O(1) ✅ | O(n) |
| **Early exit?** | Yes | Yes ✅ |
| **Interview preferred?** | No | Yes ✅ |

> The brute force wins on space but is unusable at scale. The hash set trades O(n) space for a massive time improvement — standard tradeoff in hashing problems.

