## 🔑 Tricks Learned

**Trick 1 — Hash set gives O(1) membership check**
```python
if num in seen:
```
Checking membership in a list is O(n). In a set it's O(1). This single swap is what converts the brute force into an optimal solution.

**Trick 2 — Early exit on first duplicate**
We return immediately when a duplicate is found — no need to process the rest of the array. Best case (duplicate at index 1) is O(1).

**Trick 3 — One-liner using set length**
```python
return len(set(nums)) < len(nums)
```
If the set is smaller than the original array, duplicates were removed — so one existed. Concise but processes the entire array before deciding; no early exit.

---

## The 5-Question Framework

| Question | Answer here |
|---|---|
| What do I **track**? | `seen` — a set of all numbers encountered so far |
| When do I **keep going**? | Until we find a duplicate or exhaust the array |
| What happens **each step**? | Check if `num` is in `seen`; if yes return `True`, else add it |
| What are the **edge cases**? | Empty array → `False`, single element → `False`, all duplicates → `True` early |
| What do I **return**? | `True` if duplicate found, `False` if loop completes without one |

